SPECIES COMMENTS: Excerpt from my journal: "This morning I saw an Osprey catch a fish in the pond at Quail Hollow!  It was so cool!  I had spotted the Osprey a few minutes earlier and was watching it circle the pond.  It swooped, then aborted half way down, circled some more, and swooped in for the kill.  Unfortunately, the bird went behind some trees that were in the way, so I didn't actually see it hit the water, but I was close enough to clearly hear the splash.  It was out of my sight for just a very few seconds, and then reappeared, with a fish in its talons.  And, just like the Osprey in David Attenborough's 'The Life of Birds' video, the Osprey arranged the fish in its talons so that the fish's head was pointing forward, to minimize drag as she/he took her meal off to the northwest.  It was quite a show, brief though it was."

Chris Dodson, Jeremy Dunford (age 10 almost), and I went camping with Bruce and Susan DeTerra and their kids, Lauren and Julian, arriving Aug 16 and departing Aug. 19.  Our family had camp site D-18.  We spent much time around the camp sites and down at the lake, but we also drove to other locations and walked or hiked: Bruce and I hiked to the top of Lassen Peak, then all of us walked to the sulphur springs nearby.  We also did a night event (a few miles from our campsite along the road toward Lassen Peak trial and the sulphur springs) with an astronomy club and observed stars and planets through powerful telescopes of the club members. A chase of C. Greenshank found by Ken Irwin ~a week earlier. Rita, Dan Singer, and I drove up Friday night, 31 Aug, and overnighted with David Fix & Jude Powers. Next day they were off to Washington state, and we went out to search for the bird. John Luther told us it was being seen from backyard of 1876 Ocean in McKinleyville, which overlooks the Mad River estuary, and there it was. We spent 1.5 hours scoping it (and taking distant photos) with other birders; the checklist is just the flock of birds it was with. I have sketch, description, and distant photos of this juv C. TRIP COMMENTS: Observers: Mark Holmgren, Melissa Kelly for full time; assisted by Joan Hardie, Liz Mason, Pat McNulty.--Intent: This effort was to scout a suitable Big Sit! site for future Big Sit!s. The purpose is to count from dawn to dusk from a 17’ diameter circle all the species one can detect. We stayed at our site from 0650 till 1115 then again from 1730 to 1830 hours, 5 hrs, 25 min total. Total species seen was 69, but we deviated from our site to determine the best site. From our one site we saw 69 species in total; 68 were seen from the circle (the Merlin was seen from outside the circle). We suspect that this number can be improved upon later in the fall.--Coverage: Our circle is centered on the N edge of highway 154 opposite 4500 Star Route and W from a large rectangular regulatory road sign. Used 22x Leica scope and binoculars to see mountains and lake.--Conditions: Excellent. It was very warm 70o during the night on top of the mountain, but perhaps in the 50os when we started our count. Foggy for much of the time till 0750. Clear from then on.--Significant Observations: We watched a bobcat make a feeble attempt at the geese on the N side of the river delta. As the Bobcat walked away a Great Egret hovered over it. I had not seen that behavior previously. Both Western and Clark’s Grebes are still involved in some sort of breeding although no nests were seen. The adult kites seen were together in the vicinity of a previous nest site in cottonwoods on the N side of the delta.--Mammals: Bobcat seen on N side river on delta, Family of 5 raccoons on S side delta.

TRIP COMMENTS: Birding with Morgan Ball. Weather: No cloud cover, no wind. Coverage:  All observations were made with some haste due to our need to be accompanied by Rob Berkshire because of increased security concerns. Therefore, counts of abundant species are very approximate.  We did not spend time distinguishing any odd scaup that might be present.  We walked across Bradbury Dam from the S to the N side then back to the S end.  We paid special attention to the artificial embayment at the far N end of the dam.  We did not cover the marshes or riparian on the SYR to the W of the dam, but we did scope into the area counting waterfowl in the marshes below the dam.  We did not check out the Sewage treatment ponds. All observations visual unless otherwise noted.  Some terrestrial birds from the vicinity of the dam tenders office were included. Original notes reside at the UCSB Center for Biodiversity and Ecological Restoration Field Note Archive: C:\FIELDNOT\Bradbury 27 Dec 2001.pdf
